# Derivatives of Bezier Curves
#math #cs 
> [[Investigating Bezier Curves|Investigating Bezier Curves]], [[Bernstein Polynomial Form|Bernstein Polynomial Form]]

# Formula
$$
\boxed{
\begin{align}
&P'(t) =\\
&\textcolor{red}{P_{0}}\cdot
(-3t^{2}+6t-3 &)\,+\\
&\textcolor{Turquoise}{P_{1}}\cdot
(9t^{2}-12t+3 &)\,+\\
&\textcolor{JungleGreen}{P_{2}}\cdot
(-9t^{2}+6t &)\,+\\
&\textcolor{orange}{P_{3}}\cdot
(3t^{2} &)\,+\\

\end{align}
}
$$
# Derivative of what exactly?
We can look at the [[Bernstein Polynomial Form| Bernstein Polynomial Form]] for a given bezier curve, and determine the derivative that way: 
$P'(t)$
![Pasted image 20220112202627.png](data:image/png;base64,)
this can also be considered the velocity of a Bezier curve.
# Why is this useful?
The derivative gives us the tangent to a Bezier curve:
![Pasted image 20220112202257.png](data:image/png;base64,)
and by converting this to a unit vector we can then also find the normal vector to the bezier curve by rotating it $90\degree$:
![Pasted image 20220112202353.png](data:image/png;base64,)
### For Computer Graphics:
This allows us to start getting **local coordinates** that are **offset from the curve**! 
This is the key to getting offset points for generating geometry!
![Pasted image 20220112202549.png](data:image/png;base64,)
### For Bounding Box:
The derivative of a Bezier curve is also used in [[Bounding Box of A Bezier Curve|finding its bounding box]], which can be super useful in optimization of game code for example. *But who would possibly need to use it for that* .
